We have one token: the string representation of `ans`. Then the second program counts the tokens until it finds a "0", and outputs the index (if found) or the total count if not? But note: the second program breaks when it finds a "0", so if it doesn't find a zero, it will output the total count of tokens? However, the code in the second program:

            String[] input_array = br.readLine().split(" ");
            int result = 0;
            for (String str : input_array) {
                result += 1; if ("0".equals(str)) break;
            }

        So if the token is not "0", then after the first token, result becomes 1 and then the loop ends because there are no more tokens? Then it outputs 1.

The token is stored without leading/trailing spaces. Then we use s(i:i) for i from 1 to n. But what if the string we read has length not equal to n? The Java program: 
        n = sc.nextInt();
        a = new int[n];
        for (int i=0; i<n; i++) a[i] = sc.nextInt();
        s = sc.next();

   Then s.length() is the length of the token. The problem says the string s has length n? Example input: 
        3
        1 2 3
        BAB

   Then s = "BAB", which has length 3 -> n. But what if the input for the string is "B A B"? Then sc.next() would read "B", then we have two more tokens? That would break because the array a is of size 3
